{"id":"2304.10873","submitter":"V. O. Nesterenko","authors":"V.O. Nesterenko, M.A. Mardyban, P.-G. Reinhard, A. Repko and J. Kvasil","title":"Anomalous deformation dependence of moments of inertia in light deformed\n  nuclei","comments":"12 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th nucl-ex","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the deformation dependence of the moment of inertia $\\cal J$\nfor light nuclei $^{24}$Mg and $^{20}$Ne and find regimes where $\\cal J$\ndecreases with increasing the axial quadrupole deformation $\\beta$, at variance\nwith the generally expected increasing trend. The study is based on quadrupole\nconstrained calculations using three cranking approaches for $\\cal J$\n(Inglis-Belyaev, Thouless-Valatin, adiabatic time-dependent Hartree-Fock) and\nrepresentative set of Skyrme forces (SVbas, SkM* and SLy6). The calculations\ncover a wide deformation range 0 $< \\beta < $ 1.2. The anomalous regime with\n$d{\\cal J}/d\\beta<0$ starts at about $\\beta=0.5$ for $^{24}$Mg and $\\beta=0.7$\nfor $^{20}$Ne, where the pairing already breaks down. The unusual trend of\n$\\cal J$ is explained by a shell structure effect: specific evolution of few\ndominant particle-hole (1ph) configurations with $\\beta$. The analysis of\nexperimental data for the ground-state rotational bands in $^{24}$Mg and\n$^{20}$Ne shows that such anomalous effect indeed can take place at low spins.\nFor comparison, the dependence ${\\cal J}(\\beta)$ in a standard medium-mass\ndeformed nucleus $^{170}$Hf is also inspected.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Apr 2023 10:36:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-24"}
